\n| style=\"background:#228B22;\" |\t[[Lyon County, Nevada|Lyon]]\t        ||47.62%||     80|| 52.38%|| 88\n|-\n| style=\"background:#D4AA00;\" |\t[[Mineral County, Nevada|Mineral]]\t        ||53.42%||     39|| 46.58%|| 34\n|-\n| style=\"background:#D4AA00;\" |\t[[Nye County, Nevada|Nye]]\t        ||58.75%||     94|| 40.63%|| 65\n|-\n| style=\"background:#228B22;\" |\t[[Pershing County, Nevada|Pershing]]\t        ||47.76%||    32|| 49.25%|| 33\n|-\n| style=\"background:#228B22;\" |\t[[Storey County, Nevada|Storey]]\t        ||47.95%||     35|| 52.05%|| 38\n|-\n| style=\"background:#228B22;\" |\t[[Washoe County, Nevada|Washoe]]\t        ||45.70%||     877|| 54.25%|| 1,041\n|-\n| style=\"background:#D4AA00;\" |\t[[White Pine County, Nevada|White Pine]]\t        ||50.54%||     47|| 49.46%|| 46\n|-\n|                             |'''Total'''||'''52.64%'''||'''6,440'''|| 47.29% ||5,785\n|-\n|}\nSource:<ref>http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/</ref>\n\n== Analysis ==\nClinton won the popular vote handily in the Nevada caucus, after a rough start to the primary season. With a razor-thin victory in [[Iowa Democratic caucuses, 2016|Iowa]] and a crushing defeat in [[New Hampshire Democratic primary, 2016|New Hampshire]], Clinton rebounded to a five-point-win in the Silver State aided by late campaigning among casino workers. As [[The New York Times]] describes, \"At a caucus at the famed [[Caesars Palace]], [[blackjack]] dealers, pit bosses, cooks and housekeepers excitedly declared their support for the former secretary of state.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/21/us/politics/nevada-caucus.html|title=Hillary Clinton Beats Bernie Sanders in Nevada Caucuses|last=Chozick|first=Amy|date=2016-02-20|last2=Healy|first2=Patrick|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=2016-10-21}}</ref>\n\nClinton had campaigned heavily in the state, airing an ad in which she comforted a young [[Latin Americans|Latina]] girl who was worried her parents would be [[Deportation|deported]]. Clinton's message appeared to resonate with [[Hispanic]] and [[African Americans|African American]] voters, with Clinton winning by large margins in many diverse neighborhoods in populous [[Clark County, Nevada|Clark County]], especially in caucuses in [[Las Vegas]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{2016 Democratic primaries}}\n\n[[Category:2016 United States Democratic presidential primaries by state|Nevada]]\n[[Category:Nevada Democratic caucuses|2016]]\n[[Category:2016 Nevada elections|Democratic caucuses]]\n[[Category:Political conventions in Nevada|Democratic, 2016]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox election\n| election_name = 2016 Nevada Democratic caucuses\n| country = Nevada\n| type = presidential\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = 2008 Nevada Democratic caucuses\n| previous_year = 2008\n| next_election = 2020 Nevada Democratic caucuses\n| next_year = 2020\n| votes_for_election = 43 [[2016 Democratic National Convention|Democratic National Convention]] delegates<br/>(35 pledged, 8 unpledged)\n| election_date = {{Start date|2016|02|20}}\n| image1 = [[File:Hillary Clinton by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg|120px]]\n| candidate1 = '''[[Hillary Clinton]]'''\n| color1 = d4aa00\n| home_state1 = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| delegate_count1 = '''20'''\n| percentage1 = '''52.64%'''\n| image2 = [[File:Bernie Sanders September 2015 cropped.jpg|120px]]\n| candidate2 = [[Bernie Sanders]]\n| color2 = 228B22\n| home_state2 = [[Vermont]]\n| delegate_count2 = 15\n| percentage2 = 47.29%\n| map_image = Nevada Democratic Presidential Caucuses Election Results by County, 2016.svg\n| map_size = 275px\n| map_caption  = Election results by county.{{legend|#d4aa00|Hillary Clinton}}\n{{legend|#228B22|Bernie Sanders}}{{legend|#666666|Tie}}\n}}\n\nThe '''2016 Nevada Democratic caucuses''' took place on February 20 in the U.S. state of [[Nevada]], traditionally marking the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]]'s third nominating contest in their series of [[Democratic Party presidential primaries, 2016|presidential primaries]] ahead of the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]]. The [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] held its [[South Carolina Republican primary, 2016|South Carolina primary]] on the same day, while their own [[Nevada Republican caucuses, 2016|Nevada caucuses]] took place on February 23.\n\nWith all other candidates having dropped out of the race ahead of the Nevada caucuses, the two remaining candidates were [[Bernie Sanders]] and [[Hillary Clinton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nvdems.com/caucus/candidates/|title=2016 Candidates|publisher=NVDems|date=2014-06-20|accessdate=2016-05-21}}</ref>\n\n==Process==\n[[File:Washoe County Democratic Convention 2016 (25925609250).jpg|thumb|Tension arises at the Washoe County Democratic Convention 2016, between Sanders supporters in front and Clinton supporters behind.]]\nOf the total number of 43 delegates the Nevada Democratic Party may send to the [[2016 Democratic National Convention]], 35 are pledged and 8 are unpledged.\n\nThe delegate selection process is a system with three levels:\n# The first step in the delegate selection process were the precinct caucuses on February 20, which elected about 12,000 delegates to the county conventions.\n# At the county conventions on April 2, the county delegates selected about 4,000 delegates to the state convention.\n# At the state convention on May 14\u201315, the final 35 pledged delegates to the National Convention will be selected. 23 of them are allocated proportionally based on congressional district results, whereas the remaining 12 are allocated based on the state convention as a whole.\n\n==State convention==\nThe state convention was held in May as the final stage of the delegate selection process. Supporters of Sanders believed that the convention rules, which had been largely the same for the previous 8 years, gave an unfair amount of power to the convention chair. The rules specifically lay out that all convention votes must be done by voice vote, and that only the convention chair can declare the winner or call for a more specific method of voting among the thousands of delegates. During the vote the convention chair, Roberta Lange accepted the \"yeas\" even though the \"nays\" were louder than the \"yeas\" in the room. However both preliminary and final delegate counts showed that Clinton supporters outnumbered Sanders supporters in the room. Once Lange accepted the \"yeas\", upset Sanders supporters rushed the main stage, yelling obscenities at Lange and other members of the party\u2019s executive board. The event was quickly shut down after that. Casino spokeswoman Jennifer Forkis said the event ran over its allotted time by about four hours, meaning security hired for the event would soon leave their shifts. \"Without adequate security personnel, and in consultation with the Las Vegas Metropolitan Police Department and event organizers, a decision was made that it was in the best interest of everyone in attendance to end the event,\" Forkis said in a statement.<ref>https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2016/may/18/jeff-weaver/allegations-fraud-and-misconduct-nevada-democratic/</ref>\n\n==Debates and forums==\n===October 2015 debate in Las Vegas===\n{{main|First Democratic Party presidential debate, October 2015 in Las Vegas, Nevada}}\n\nOn October 13, 2015, the Democratic Party's very first debate was held at the [[Wynn Las Vegas|Wynn Hotel]] in [[Las Vegas]]. Hosted by [[Anderson Cooper]], it aired on [[CNN]] and was broadcast on radio by [[Westwood One (current)|Westwood One]]. Participants were the candidates [[Hillary Clinton]], [[Bernie Sanders]], [[Jim Webb]], [[Martin O'Malley]], and [[Lincoln Chafee]]. It was the first and only debate appearance of Chafee and Webb, who ended their campaigns on October 23 and October 20, respectively.\n\n===February 2016 forum in Las Vegas===\n{{See also|Democratic Party presidential debates, 2016}}\nOn February 18, MSNBC and Telemundo hosted a forum in Las Vegas.\n\n==Opinion polling==\n{{see also|Statewide opinion polling for the Democratic Party presidential primaries, 2016}}\n\nDelegate count: 35 Pledged, 8 [[Superdelegate|Unpledged]]\n;Winner: [[File:America Symbol.svg|14px]] Hillary Clinton \n;Caucus date: February 20, 2016\n\n{{Nevada Democratic primary polls, 2016}}\n\n==Results==\nPrimary date: February 20, 2016<br>\nCounty conventions: April 2, 2016<br>\nState convention: May 14, 2016<br>\nNational delegates: 43\n\n{{2016NVDem}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:12px;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\"| Nevada Democratic county conventions, April 2, 2016\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Candidate\n! colspan=\"2\" | State delegates\n! colspan=\"3\" | Estimated delegates\n|-\n! style=\"width:70px;\" | Count\n! style=\"width:80px;\" | Percentage\n! style=\"width:45px;\" | <small>Pledged</small>\n! style=\"width:45px;\" | <small>Unpledged</small>\n! style=\"width:45px;\" | <small>Total</small>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Bernie Sanders presidential campaign, 2016|Bernie Sanders]]\n|2,124\n|55.23%\n|17\n|1\n|18\n|- \n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Hillary Clinton presidential campaign, 2016|Hillary Clinton]]\n| 1,722\n| 44.77%\n| 18\n| 4\n| 22\n|- \n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Uncommitted\n| 0\n| 0.00%\n| 0\n| 3\n| 3\n|-\n! Total\n! \n! 100%\n! 35\n! 8\n! 43\n|-\n| colspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:left;\" | Source: ''The Moderate Voice''<ref>{{cite web | url=http://themoderatevoice.com/what-just-happened-in-nevada | title=What just happened in Nevada? Did Sanders suddenly beat Clinton? | work=The Moderate Voice | last=Gill | first=Kathy | date=3 April 2016 | accessdate=5 April 2016}}</ref>\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:12px;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\"| Nevada Democratic state conventions, May 14, 2016\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Candidate\n!